soc.message

Class SOCTurn

  • java.lang.Object
    • soc.message.SOCMessage
      • soc.message.SOCMessageForGame
        • soc.message.SOCTurn
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable

    public class SOCTurn
extends SOCMessageForGame
    This message from server to client signals end of the current player's turn. Client should end current turn, clear dice, set current player number, reset votes, etc.

    In v2.0.00 and newer, this message optionally includes a getGameState() field instead of a separate SOCGameState message, since the state and turn are part of the same transition.

    Before v2.0.00 this message was always preceded by a SOCGameState with the new turn's state. There were a few minor messages like SOCSetPlayedDevCard sent between them. Client would set current game state based on that GAMESTATE message. Then, when this TURN message changed the player number, the game would have a known state to inform the new player's options and actions.

    In v2.0.00 and newer, is also sent to robot players during initial placement when a round ends and the direction of play changes, and bot has just placed a road or ship and should now place the next settlement or roll the dice as first player. (In earlier versions with fewer possible state transitions, the client's SOCGame had enough info to advance the gamestate and player number.)

    Before v2.0.00 the server didn't send a TURN message to human players after the final road or ship is placed at the end of initial placement and start of regular gameplay, only a SOCGameState message (state START2 -> PLAY/ROLL_OR_CARD).

    Author:
    Robert S. Thomas
    See Also:
    SOCSetTurn, Serialized Form

      • toString

        public java.lang.String toString()
        Description copied from class: SOCMessage
        Simple human-readable delimited representation, used for debug purposes: SOCPutPiece:game=test5|playerNumber=3|pieceType=0|coord=40a
        Could also be used by a SOCServer.recordGameEvent(String, SOCMessage) implementation.

        Within this representation, message parameters should be in same order used by SOCMessage.toCmd() and parseDataStr(..). Should be parseable by SOCMessage.parseMsgStr(String) which calls SOCMessage.stripAttribNames(String), which your class can override if needed.

        Overrides:
        toString in class SOCMessageForGame
        Returns:
        a human readable form of the message
        See Also:
        SOCMessage.toCmd()
